[Patient] What foods should I eat to manage my heart failure?
[Healthcare Educator] Focus on fruits, veggies, whole grains, lean proteins, and limit sodium for a heart-healthy diet.
[Patient] Can I still enjoy my favorite foods?
[Healthcare Educator] Yes, you can. Let's find ways to make them healthier with small changes.
[Patient] How can I control my portion sizes?
[Healthcare Educator] Use smaller plates, measure servings, and listen to your body's hunger cues.
[Patient] What about snacks? Any recommendations?
[Healthcare Educator] Opt for nuts, fruits, yogurt, or whole grain crackers for heart-healthy snacking options.
[Patient] How important is it to limit sodium intake?
[Healthcare Educator] Very important. High sodium can worsen heart failure symptoms. Try flavoring with herbs instead.
[Patient] Are there any cooking classes available?
[Healthcare Educator] Yes, we can help you find cooking classes that focus on heart-healthy recipes.
[Patient] How can I make my meals more flavorful without adding salt?
[Healthcare Educator] Use herbs, spices, lemon juice, or vinegar to enhance the taste of your dishes.
[Patient] What should I drink to stay hydrated?
[Healthcare Educator] Water is the best choice. Limit sugary drinks and alcohol for heart health.
[Patient] Can I still have desserts?
[Healthcare Educator] Yes, in moderation. Try fruit-based desserts or small portions of your favorites.
[Patient] How often should I eat throughout the day?
[Healthcare Educator] Aim for regular meals and snacks to keep your energy levels stable.
[Patient] Any tips for dining out at restaurants?
[Healthcare Educator] Look for dishes with grilled or steamed options, and ask for dressings or sauces on the side.
[Patient] What about fast food? Can I still have it occasionally?
[Healthcare Educator] It's best to limit fast food due to high sodium and unhealthy fats. Choose healthier options when possible.
[Patient] Thank you for all the helpful tips. I'll work on making these changes. 
[Healthcare Educator] You're welcome. Remember, small changes can lead to big improvements in your heart health. Stay motivated!